	(text "star-ground leg 3"
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 124 213 0)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.6 1.6)
			)
			(justify left)
		)
		(uuid "5a170005-0000-4000-8000-000000000029")
	)
	(text_box "3.3 V ONLY - AND PIN 2 OF THIS HEADER IS 5 V\n\nEvery GPIO on J8 is a 3.3 V pin and none of them is 5 V tolerant. From the\nRaspberry Pi documentation: \"The remaining pins are all general-purpose 3.3 V pins,\nmeaning outputs are set to 3.3 V and inputs are 3.3V-tolerant\", and, plainly,\n\"Do not use 5V for 3.3V components.\"\n\nThere is no clamp that will save you. Over-voltage on a GPIO triggers latch-up in\nthe pad driver, which shorts the 3V3 rail to ground inside the silicon. The board\ndoes not recover.\n\nAND THE 5 V PINS ARE THE CLOSEST PINS ON THE HEADER:\n\n     pin  1   3V3            pin  2   5V     <-- directly opposite 3V3\n     pin  3   GPIO2  SDA1    pin  4   5V     <-- and again\n     pin  5   GPIO3  SCL1    pin  6   GND\n     pin  7   GPIO4          pin  8   GPIO14 / TXD0     sheet 6\n     pin  9   GND            pin 10   GPIO15 / RXD0     sheet 6\n     pin 11   GPIO17         pin 12   GPIO18            <-- D1, this sheet\n     pin 13   GPIO27         pin 14   GND               <-- SW2, this sheet\n     pin 15   GPIO22         pin 16   GPIO23\n     pin 17   3V3            pin 18   GPIO24\n\nPin 1 is the square pad, at the end of the header nearest the micro-SD card. The\nodd-numbered pins are one row and the even-numbered pins the other. Take 3V3 from\npin 1 or 17 and GND from pin 6, 9 or 14.\n\nA one-position slip on the even row - pin 2 or pin 4 instead of the ground you\nmeant - puts 5 V straight onto a 3.3 V rail. Confirm pin 1 against the silkscreen\nand ring out your ground with a meter before applying power."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 300 40 0)
		(size 274 71)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 214 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5a170005-0000-4000-8000-00000000002a")
	)
	(text_box "THE BUTTON - AND THE INTERNAL PULL-DOWN IT HAS TO BEAT\n\nGPIO27 powers up as an input with a DEFAULT PULL-DOWN of 50-65 kohm. Both halves of\nthat come from primary sources: BCM2835 ARM Peripherals table 6-31 lists GPIO9\nthrough GPIO27 as \"Low\", and the Raspberry Pi GPIO documentation gives RPD = 50-65\nkohm. Every GPIO on this header has some default pull, and firmware has not run yet\nwhen you first apply power.\n\nR5 is therefore not a formality. It has to win a divider against a pull-down that is\nalready there, at the worst corner - RPD at its 50 kohm minimum, where it is\nstrongest:\n\n  released   node = 3.3 V x 50k / (4.7k + 50k)              = 3.02 V\n  pressed    node = 3.3 V x (470 || 50k) / (4.7k + 465)     = 0.30 V\n\nagainst the Pi's thresholds of VIH min 1.6 V and VIL max 0.9 V: 1.4 V of margin\nhigh, 0.6 V low. Active low - the same polarity as the Due's wall switch, on purpose.\n\nPICK R5 = 47 kohm INSTEAD - a value that would be entirely sensible on a part with no\ninternal pull - and the released level becomes 3.3 x 50/97 = 1.70 V, which is 0.1 V\nabove VIH min. It would work on the bench and fail at the other end of the tolerance\nband, intermittently, in a way that looks like a debounce bug.\n\nR6 and C4 are the same network, for the same reasons, as the Due's wall switch on\nsheet 4: R6 caps the capacitor discharge through the contacts at 3.3 V / 470 ohm =\n7.0 mA, and the pair filters sub-millisecond chatter into a monotonic edge. Time\nconstants 0.43 ms rising, 43 us falling. The Pi's pads have selectable Schmitt-trigger\ninput filtering, which firmware should leave enabled.\n\nSW2 IS MOMENTARY. Unlike SW1 it has a rest state it returns to, and only its closing\nedge is an event."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 300 117 0)
		(size 274 73.2)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 249 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5a170005-0000-4000-8000-00000000002b")
	)
	(text_box "THE STATUS LED - AND WHY IT IS DARK BEFORE THE PI BOOTS\n\nD1 is active high: driving GPIO17 high lights it.\n\n  I = (3.3 V - 1.9 V) / 1 kohm = 1.4 mA\n\nThe Pi guarantees VOH >= 3.0 V at 2 mA on its default 8 mA drive strength, so 1.4 mA\nsits well inside that and the real current is nearer 1.1 mA. Dim, and unmistakable\nindoors. 330 ohm, about 4 mA, is the practical floor if you want it brighter - still\nhalf the default drive strength and a quarter of the 16 mA maximum. Only one pin\nsources current on this board, so the aggregate GPIO budget is not a constraint here.\nIt would be, with a bar of eight.\n\nDARK BEFORE FIRMWARE RUNS, for free. The Raspberry Pi documentation: \"All GPIO pins\nrevert to general-purpose inputs on power-on reset. The default pull states are also\napplied\". GPIO17's default pull is Low. So at power-on the pin is an input held down\nby a 50-65 kohm pull-down, the LED sees leakage, and it is off.\n\nThat is the same guarantee R2 buys for the light on sheet 3 - except here it comes\nfree with the silicon's reset state, and there it had to be built out of a resistor\nand defended against the SAM3X's reset state, which pulls the other way. Worth\nnoticing that the two boards default in opposite directions; it is the kind of thing\nthat is obvious on a diagram and invisible in code."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 300 196.2 0)
		(size 274 55.6)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 255 249 214 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5a170005-0000-4000-8000-00000000002c")
	)
	(text_box "WHICH PI, AND WHICH GPIOs\n\nDrawn against the 40-pin J8 header, which is electrically and mechanically\nidentical across Raspberry Pi 2, 3, 4, 5 and Zero 2 W. Nothing on this sheet\nchanges with the model.\n\nThe reference build is a RASPBERRY PI 3 MODEL B+ (BCM2837B0, Cortex-A53). What\nthat pins down is firmware-side, not wiring-side - the target triple, the kernel\nimage name, the ARM load address and the peripheral base - and it belongs to the\nbare-metal boot story. This sheet does not constrain any of it.\n\nWHY GPIO17 AND GPIO27, and not simply the first two free pins:\n\n*  Neither has a boot-time role. Nothing samples them at reset, and neither is\n   used by the GPU or the firmware blobs.\n*  Neither carries an alternate function this system needs. GPIO17's alternates\n   are RTS0 and SPI1_CE1_N; GPIO27's are SD1_DAT3 and ARM_TMS. None is in play.\n*  Both default to a pull-DOWN, which is what makes the LED dark at power-on and\n   what R5 is sized against for the button.\n*  They sit next to the UART pins used on sheet 6, so one harness reaches all four.\n\nAVOID GPIO0 and GPIO1, pins 27 and 28: they are the HAT ID EEPROM lines and are\nread at boot. AVOID GPIO2 and GPIO3, pins 3 and 5: they have fixed on-board\npull-ups that cannot be turned off."
		(exclude_from_sim no)
		(at 20 232 0)
		(size 270 57.8)
		(margins 1.27 1.27 1.27 1.27)
		(stroke
			(width 0.254)
			(type default)
		)
		(fill
			(type color)
			(color 224 240 255 1)
		)
		(effects
			(font
				(size 1.27 1.27)
			)
			(justify left top)
		)
		(uuid "5a170005-0000-4000-8000-00000000002d")
	)
